{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526032"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:32:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:32:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.15,0.08,0.07,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52636"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6795"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37999"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15169"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45742"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52636"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of sudden onset palpitations. She has no chest pain or shortness of breath. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She denies any recreational drug use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious but otherwise well. Her pulse rate is 180/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a regular tachycardia with no murmurs. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. An ECG shows a narrow complex tachycardia at 150/min with no discernible P waves (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vagal manoeuvres","Intravenous metoprolol","Intravenous amiodarone","Intravenous adenosine","Synchronised cardioversion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a narrow complex tachycardia, which is likely supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) given the sudden onset, regular rhythm, and rate \u0026gt;150/min. The patient is haemodynamically stable, so immediate electrical cardioversion is not necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate first step in management is to perform \u003Cstrong\u003Evagal manoeuvres\u003C/strong\u003E. These include the Valsalva manoeuvre or carotid sinus massage, which can terminate SVT by increasing parasympathetic tone and slowing conduction through the AV node. Vagal manoeuvres are safe, non-invasive, and can be effective in terminating SVT in up to 25% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf vagal manoeuvres fail, \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous adenosine\u003C/strong\u003E would be the next step. Adenosine is a rapidly acting AV nodal blocking agent that can terminate most forms of SVT. It is given as a rapid bolus followed by a saline flush. While effective, it can cause transient chest discomfort and dyspnoea, so it is not the first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous metoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, can be used to control heart rate in SVT but is less effective than adenosine for acute termination. It would be considered if adenosine is contraindicated or ineffective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynchronised cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for haemodynamically unstable patients or when pharmacological methods have failed. This patient is stable, so electrical cardioversion is not the first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous amiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used for ventricular arrhythmias or atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response. It is not the first-line treatment for SVT and has a slower onset of action compared to adenosine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter attempting vagal manoeuvres, if the arrhythmia persists, the next step would be to administer adenosine. If SVT recurs or is refractory to treatment, further investigation for underlying causes and consideration of long-term management strategies would be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vagal manoeuvres are the first-line treatment for stable narrow complex supraventricular tachycardia.","Adenosine is the second-line treatment for stable narrow complex supraventricular tachycardia if vagal manoeuvres fail.","Narrow complex tachycardia with a regular rhythm and rate \u003E150min is likely to be supraventricular tachycardia."],"references":["Al-Salamah T, AlAgeel M, Alblaihed L. Narrow Complex Tachycardias. Emerg Med Clin North Am. 2022; 40:717-32."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37999"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14115"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21005"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21005"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/z99udk4vM9ZwdsEsaSU4ZF6n88TCpA.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/z99udk4vM9ZwdsEsaSU4ZF6n88TCpA.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":305}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37999"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-08T11:08:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-08T11:08:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6795"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52636"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags